Interaction of DA with sensing system has occurred through direct bonding by following TBET based principle. This can be proven with the help of surface charge analysis after the interaction of DA with sensing system. As shown in Fig. S3, the surface charges of CdTe QDs and CQDs were −21.1 mV and −10.6 mV respectively. Combination of both QDs has resulted in a significant decrease in surface potential as −17.3 that can be correlated with FTIR results to confirm the amide formation. Apart from TBET based sensing of DA the PHT based sensing mechanism has been proposed for the target based sensing approach. According to the literature [40], a strong electron donating group can effectively quench the PL intensity of QDs by its oxidation potential. Here, non-passivated Cd2+ ions from the surface of CdTe QDs directly interact with amine groups of DA due to the strong metal affinity. This interaction leads to transfer of photoexcited holes from highest occupied molecular orbital (HOMO) of the QDs to HOMO of DA and resulting in non-radiative recombination, that affects the PL intensity of QDs (Fig. 7
                        ) [41,42]. Through this strategy, selective binding of DA with QDs was achieved among the interferences. Photoinduced transfer of holes and agglomeration of QDs increases the RH of whole system up to 35 nm (Fig. S2). That also leads to significant decrement in surface charge up to −12.7 mV (Fig. S3). From this, it was proven that effective detection of DA could be achieved by simply optimizing reaction conditions without the support of additional linkers. Comparison results from existing ratiometric reports are listed in Table 1
                         to exhibit the advantages and novelty of this study.
